✅ Q1. Define Data Communication. Explain components + modes (12M)
Definition of Data Communication
Data Communication is the process of exchanging data between two or more devices through a transmission medium such as cables, wires, or wireless signals.

Five Components of Data Communication System
Sender
The device that sends the data.
Example: Computer, mobile phone.
It generates the message to be transmitted.
Receiver
The device that receives the data.
Example: Another computer or device.
It interprets the received message.
Message
The actual data being communicated.
It can be text, numbers, images, audio, or video.
Transmission Medium
The physical path through which data travels.
Examples: Twisted pair cable, fiber optic, radio waves.
Protocol
A set of rules governing data communication.
Ensures proper transmission between sender and receiver.

Modes of Data Flow
Simplex Mode
Communication is one-way only.
Example: Keyboard → Computer
No feedback from receiver.
Half Duplex Mode
Communication is two-way but not simultaneous.
Example: Walkie-talkie
Only one device transmits at a time.
Full Duplex Mode
Communication is two-way and simultaneous.
Example: Telephone call
Both sender and receiver can send data at the same time.





✅ Q2. Protocol + Elements + Topology (12M)
Definition of Protocol
A protocol is a set of rules that governs data communication. It defines how data is transmitted, what is transmitted, and when it is transmitted.

Elements of Protocol
Syntax
Refers to the structure or format of data.
Defines how data is arranged.
Semantics
Defines the meaning of each section of bits.
Includes error detection and control information.
Timing
Determines when data should be sent and at what speed.
Ensures synchronization between sender and receiver.

Network Topology
Network topology refers to the arrangement of nodes and connections in a network.

Types of Topology
1. Bus Topology
All devices connected to a single cable (backbone).
Advantages:
Low cost
Easy to install
Disadvantages:
Failure of main cable stops entire network

2. Star Topology
All devices connected to a central hub.
Advantages:
Easy to troubleshoot
Failure of one node doesn’t affect others
Disadvantages:
Hub failure crashes entire network

3. Ring Topology
Devices connected in circular form.
Data travels in one direction using token.
Disadvantage:
Failure of one node stops network

4. Mesh Topology
Every node connected to every other node.
Advantages:
High reliability
Disadvantages:
Expensive and complex

5. Tree Topology
Combination of Bus and Star.
Advantage:
Easy expansion
Disadvantage:
Backbone failure affects segments





✅ Q3. Transmission Media + Impairment + Switching (12M)
Transmission Media
Transmission medium is the path through which data travels.

Types
1. Guided Media (Wired)
Twisted Pair Cable
Cheap and widely used
Prone to noise
Coaxial Cable
Better shielding
Used in TV networks
Fiber Optic Cable
Uses light signals
High speed and long distance

2. Unguided Media (Wireless)
Radio Waves
Long distance
Used in mobile communication
Microwaves
Line-of-sight communication
Used in satellites
Infrared
Short distance
Used in remotes

Transmission Impairment
Attenuation
Loss of signal strength over distance
Distortion
Signal changes shape
Noise
Unwanted signals affecting data

Types of Switching
1. Circuit Switching
Dedicated path established
Example: Telephone
Reliable but inefficient

2. Message Switching
Entire message sent and stored
Slow due to store-and-forward

3. Packet Switching
Message divided into packets
Efficient and widely used (Internet)





✅ Q4. Single (Analog) & Composite Signals + Periodic & Aperiodic (12M)
What is a Signal?
A signal is an electrical or electromagnetic wave used to carry data from one device to another.

Single (Simple) Signal
A single signal consists of only one frequency.
It is a pure sine wave.
It has constant amplitude, frequency, and phase.
Example: Ideal sine wave.

Composite Signal
A composite signal is made up of multiple sine waves of different frequencies.
Real-world signals are always composite.
These signals can be analyzed using Fourier Analysis.
Each component has its own amplitude, frequency, and phase.

Periodic Signals
A signal that repeats itself after a fixed time period.
Has a definite pattern.
Example: Sine wave.
Characteristics:
Fixed cycle
Predictable behavior

Aperiodic (Non-periodic) Signals
A signal that does not repeat over time.
No fixed pattern.
Example: Human voice signals.

Conclusion
Signals are fundamental for communication, and understanding their types helps in efficient transmission and processing of data.






✅ Q5. Analog & Digital Signals + Conversions (12M)
Analog Signal
Continuous signal that varies smoothly over time.
Can take infinite values.
Example: Temperature, sound waves.

Digital Signal
Discrete signal with limited values (0 and 1).
Used in modern communication systems.
Example: Computer data.

Conversions

1. Digital to Analog Conversion
Converts digital data into analog signals.
Techniques:
ASK (Amplitude Shift Keying)
Amplitude changes based on data.
Sensitive to noise.
FSK (Frequency Shift Keying)
Frequency changes for 0 and 1.
More reliable than ASK.
PSK (Phase Shift Keying)
Phase of signal changes.
Most efficient and widely used.

2. Analog to Digital Conversion
PCM (Pulse Code Modulation)
Converts analog signal into digital form.
Steps:
Sampling
Quantization
Encoding
Produces accurate digital output.

Delta Modulation (DM)
Provides approximation of signal.
Simpler than PCM.
Uses staircase representation.

3. Analog to Analog Conversion
Amplitude Modulation (AM)
Amplitude varies, frequency constant.
Frequency Modulation (FM)
Frequency varies, amplitude constant.
Phase Modulation (PM)
Phase varies with signal.

Conclusion
Conversions are essential to transmit different types of data efficiently across networks.







✅ Q6. Network Devices (12M)
1. Hub
Works at Physical Layer.
Broadcasts data to all devices.
Half duplex.
Cheap but inefficient.

2. Bridge
Works at Data Link Layer.
Connects two LANs.
Uses MAC address filtering.

3. Switch
Advanced version of hub.
Works at Data Link Layer.
Sends data only to intended device.
Full duplex.
Reduces congestion.

4. Router
Works at Network Layer.
Uses IP address to route data.
Finds best path.
Connects multiple networks.

5. Gateway
Works on all OSI layers.
Connects different networks.
Acts as protocol converter.






✅ Q7. Errors & Detection (12M)
What is Error?
Error occurs when transmitted data is altered during transmission.

Types of Errors
Single-bit error
Multiple-bit error
Burst error

Error Detection Methods

1. Parity Bit
Adds extra bit to make number of 1s even/odd.
Simple but limited detection.

2. Checksum
Sum of data is calculated and sent.
Receiver verifies correctness.

3. CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check)
Uses polynomial division.
Very reliable method.

4. LRC (Longitudinal Redundancy Check)
Checks columns of data.
Detects burst errors.

5. VRC (Vertical Redundancy Check)
Checks rows of data.
Detects single-bit errors.






✅ Q8. OSI Model (12M — VERY IMPORTANT)
Definition
OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model is a 7-layer architecture used for communication.

7 Layers of OSI Model

1. Physical Layer
Transmits raw bits.
Converts data into signals.

2. Data Link Layer
Adds MAC address.
Error detection & flow control.

3. Network Layer
Adds IP address.
Routing and path selection.

4. Transport Layer
Segmentation of data.
Error & flow control.
Protocols: TCP, UDP.

5. Session Layer
Manages sessions.
Authentication & authorization.

6. Presentation Layer
Data translation.
Encryption & compression.

7. Application Layer
User interaction layer.
Examples: HTTP, FTP, SMTP.

Conclusion
OSI model helps in standardizing communication and troubleshooting networks.








✅ Q9. TCP/IP Reference Model (VERY IMPORTANT – 12M)
Definition
TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol / Internet Protocol) model is a networking model used for communication over the Internet.
 It was developed by the Department of Defense and is the basis of modern networking.

Layers of TCP/IP Model (4 Layers)

1. Application Layer
Provides interface between user and network.
Combines OSI’s Application, Presentation, Session layers.
Functions:
File transfer
Email services
Web browsing
Protocols:
HTTP (web)
FTP (file transfer)
SMTP (email)
TELNET

2. Transport Layer
Responsible for end-to-end communication.
Functions:
Segmentation of data
Flow control
Error control
Data sequencing
Protocols:
TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)
Connection-oriented
Reliable
Error checking and recovery
Slower but accurate
UDP (User Datagram Protocol)
Connectionless
Faster
No guarantee of delivery
Used in streaming, gaming

3. Internet Layer
Responsible for logical addressing and routing.
Functions:
Assigns IP address
Determines best path
Protocols:
IP (Internet Protocol)
ICMP
ARP

4. Network Access Layer
Combines Physical + Data Link layer.
Functions:
Transmission of raw data
Handles hardware addressing (MAC)
Converts data into signals

Conclusion
TCP/IP model is widely used because it is simple, flexible, and supports all modern network communications.






✅ Q10. Multiplexing (VERY IMPORTANT – 12M)
Definition
Multiplexing is a technique used to combine multiple signals into a single communication channel to improve efficiency.

Components
Multiplexer (MUX) – Combines signals
Demultiplexer (DEMUX) – Separates signals

Types of Multiplexing

1. Frequency Division Multiplexing (FDM)
Bandwidth divided into frequency bands.
Each signal uses different frequency.
Advantages:
Supports multiple users
Full duplex communication
Disadvantages:
Expensive
Interference possible

2. Time Division Multiplexing (TDM)
Channel divided into time slots.
Each user transmits in assigned time.
Advantages:
Efficient use of bandwidth
Low cost expansion
Disadvantages:
Time synchronization required
Delay possible

3. Wavelength Division Multiplexing (WDM)
Used in fiber optics.
Different wavelengths carry different signals.
Advantages:
Very high data rate
Efficient for optical networks
Disadvantages:
High cost
Complex technology

Conclusion
Multiplexing improves bandwidth utilization and allows multiple users to share a single communication channel.






✅ Q11. PSTN (Public Switched Telephone Network) (12M)
Definition
PSTN is a global network of telephone systems used for voice communication.
 It uses circuit switching to establish a dedicated communication path.

Features
Uses circuit switching
Provides voice communication
Works through telephone lines
Reliable and widely used

Working of PSTN
Caller dials number
Connection established via switching centers
Dedicated path created
Voice transmitted as analog signals
Call ends → connection released

Components
Telephone devices
Switching offices (central exchange)
Transmission lines (cables)

Advantages
Reliable communication
Wide coverage
Simple technology

Disadvantages
Uses dedicated path → inefficient
Not suitable for data transmission
Expensive for long-distance calls

Conclusion
PSTN is the traditional telephone system that laid the foundation for modern communication networks.











